The offices also include the nursery, the architects understood
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect to also hide a mini-school with everything that belongs to it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, buying toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it can be visited by the children of employees of Arch.Design.
The project-architectural company Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of important Brno buildings came from, has been calculating the space for its company mini-school since the first drawings of the building Avriopoint.
It employs almost 90 people, mostly at the age of the babyboom, and it was important for women designers and architects to be able to get back to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of shortened schedules, the nursery is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees within the framework of the social program.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to put together a demanding job with child care.
The minischool was invented by the employees of Arch.Design themselves and with the support of management they managed to obtain the grant of the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-school is funded from the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant funding (a grant of CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and provide qualified personnel and operations for two years.
After exhausting the financial aid (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to operate a mini-school for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of the project took one year and the application for the grant was significantly helped by the company Economy Rating.
Care is provided by qualified staff, the children are taken care of by a nurse and an M.S. teacher on a daily basis, so children can go to school without age restriction, yet most of them are older than 3 years.
Because it is a "miniski<0xC5><0x82>ka", there can be only 5 children at the same time, but during the day there is also more variety.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although it is a matter of individual education and care, the program charge in the mini-school is comparable to the framework program of pre-school education.
Not only do children play here, but they are also provided with high-quality teaching - from basic knowledge to preparation for school benches, English is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and drop out of stressful situations with a delayed pick-up of children from schools away from their parents’ workplace.
In this way, parents make more productive use of their working hours.
It is not surprising that here a naturally loyal relationship of the employee - the employer is created.
Arch.Design has thus become one of the Czech companies that offer a significant benefit when recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program has strengthened personal marketing.
The house from the bone fascinates even after 100 years. Look in the interiors from Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>
The roof looks like the back of an ancient lizard, the staircase resembles the back of a dinosaur and the balconies are open fish mouth.
Such is the house Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the local house has earned the nickname House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, chunks of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of gravel and ubiquitous soft curves, all this is typical of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>'s secession.
The front of the house plays out dream lines, soft colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
When observing in detail, you can see the geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade of the house sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated in such a way that the impression of the brightness of colors is reinforced even more.
Bending and twisting of shapes with the same measure also appears in the interiors.
The wood in the waves copies the window frames, handrails, decorative elements of the door, a doll and a fox.
The Batll<0xC3><0xB3> House, which stands in Eixample district on the busy shopping street of Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA1>cia No. 43, was created by the reconstruction of the house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took place two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>'s house was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> himself.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was on his design board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the property owner and the use of mosaics on the facade were created.
A number of other artists and artists also worked on the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade.
The joint work on the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> house’s designs started the successful cooperation between Jujola and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> House Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> and the G<0xC3><0xBC>ell Park, in which Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s other works are included.
From the locals the house of the back after completion served thanks to its organic shapes the nickname "House of the Bone".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it a "living house".
It is also said that the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted at the top of the building.
The hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed a unique central heating system with ventilation ducts and typical chimneys for his time.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five-degree inclination.
At the time of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s creation, he absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, however, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, at the completion of the building, the city council was overthrown and requested a correction.
For example, the council was concerned that the building was jammed with pillars even in the public corridor.
The correction never occurred, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the appeal of the city district, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> applied for (and successfully obtained) a permit to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social lounge and on the third floor there was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to the jewellers.
The entire six-storey house crosses the staircase, which can rise up to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the cancellation of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors and a larger company can communicate comfortably together without at the same time not keeping the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, the house with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s reconstruction also received non-traditional roofing and two additional floors.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s game is also impressive with light, blue and white glazed tiles, with which the inner courtyard is covered, and lamps.
The game of two colors provides maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough simply to bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> House, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house, the most spacious and dignified apartment is made available to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the one hundred and fiftyth anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
During the tours, they persisted, as they found that it was a very advantageous business and in addition, the tours expanded on the common and underfloor spaces, including the roof terraces.
Admission to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist visas have a 20% discount.
The sum significantly exceeds the price of the entrance to other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of the house with dragon towers, you need to quickly comrade with one of the inhabitants of the renter and visit him directly at home.
