China is committed to its goal of reducing greenhouse gas emissions
The country’s representative at the UN climate change conference COP16 assured that his country had developed an extraordinary effort to reduce the carbon footprint, and said it would take 40 to 45 percent of its pledge to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 2020.
China will keep its promise to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent in 2020, Su Wei, the country’s representative at the UN climate change conference, said.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, Su Wei assured that his country had developed an immense effort to reduce the carbon footprint and transform its industry.
He said his country had already invested $245 million over the past four years in an effort to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China will not change its goals and will continue to work on this issue with the international community.
He reported that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into the following four items: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
In all these points, progress has already been made, including last year’s approval of the new Energy Act, which includes the proposed targets for reducing greenhouse gas emissions, he explained.
He also stressed that in China, the federal authorities have cooperated in coordination with provincial and local authorities to achieve their goals in terms of energy savings, energy efficiency and emission reduction.
Further, he said, various multi-year plans are underway or have already been completed, which are funded by both the Chinese government and the governments of other states.
For example, it is, as he said, a program for the efficient use of energy, which has been introduced over the past five years, and which has received investments from the UN, the government and private initiatives.
There is also a provincial project on climate change, the project on the exchange of bulbs for energy-saving bulbs and the project on mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country’s expert climate change adviser, assured that China’s efforts were greater than generally thought.
For example, he explained, greenhouse gas emissions per capita represent 6 tons in China, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9% of the historical share of emissions.
It has also developed unprecedented efforts in terms of energy use – for example, it has increased energy efficiency by 20% over the past five years and expects to make further progress by 2020, he added.
