The United States changes the rules for granting visas
People will have to contact the Visa Application Centres before the interview at the Consular Office; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be shortened.
From January 10, 2011, the visa negotiation process at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to contact the Visa Application Service Centre (ASC) even before the interview at the Consular Office.
The ASC staff will retrieve the applicant’s biometric information and they will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have some advantages, including the following:
The total cost of obtaining a visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay the fee for the appointment, the second for the processing of the application and the other for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant will only pay a single fee that covers all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the amount corresponding to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for cases of visa applications (including a temporary worker visa) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only turn to the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and will be taken fingerprints.
Given that biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at consulates in Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra fee for a service of $26.
For more information on the new visa application procedure visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
