The World Plan for the Restoration of Lighting
The United Nations has proposed a plan to restore home lighting, trade lighting and industrial spaces in 100 countries in Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n in order to achieve a greenhouse gas (GHG) limit, which corresponds to almost a third of the next limit to be reached in 2020 for climate stabilisation.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of difficult to implement commitments to reduce on the part of industrially developed countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the flared bulbs, which monopolize another 50 to 70% of the market, replace the bulbs with fluorescent or, even better, the bulbs with electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), the essential quantities of the bulbs will be emitted from 1 billion tons.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of the world's emissions.
That’s equivalent to 70% of the world’s car park emissions.
In Kodani last year, a large country with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, took part in voluntary reduction plans that would allow global GHG emissions to drop from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract from this balance another 5 Gt to achieve by 2020 climate stabilisation at 2 degrees Celsius so that it can be ruled out that it will not get out of control.
In heated bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissolved in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%,is a product of light.
With fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, we reduce this consumption twice more.
Fluorocompact bulbs last on average from 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, which were introduced this week to Philips - this company is said to have participated in the UN study - have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives us the idea of a 100-year-old bulb with a possible wear and tear.
All of these new bulbs can also work with refractory and radiate less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries, unless the manufacturers set up a collection.
However, as the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a flu-compact bulb, but rather a thermal coal power plant, which discharges many of the mercury needed to produce the electricity consumed in ignited bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants produce 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report also details the benefits that each country would receive from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would thus save $1 billion a year for the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, the construction of which would cost 2.5 billion.
