Climate: How France Hacked Its Financing Promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to test compliance with promises for fast-locked financing (spoken fast-start or premature financing), implemented by developed countries.
And the great French hacks have been revealed
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion for three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (that is 420 million per year).
At the start of the COP16 the EU has drawn a great deal of attention to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: a report detailing the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparent operations are invaluable and valued at their true value: the developed countries and civil society would like all the developed countries and civil society to do the same and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, leading it to the right path to deliver on its promise of 7.2 billion euros in 2012.
But if we focus on detail, we will find that things are much more complicated.
These funds are "new and additional" under the Copenhagen Agreement to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without the detriment of the Public Development Assistance (ODA).
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what is meant by “new and additional”.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 to be the reference year: international funding has been maintained and it adds another 150 million to the three-year fast-start funding title.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or with deadlines at the level of public development aid.
On the other hand, France believes that funding for “all new projects” in 2010 is “new and additional”.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of the Public Aid for Development d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the overall level of France's support for developing countries may remain unchanged (or even be reduced) and must comply with its commitment to finance "new and additional" countries.
Another crucial element is the distribution of gifts and loans.
There is no rule there yet, and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, believe that 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed is equal to 1 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> donated.
Obviously, this is hard to prove: effort is not comparable.
If the use of a loan can be proven for some investments that are profitable (often related to projects related to the reduction of emissions, based on more effective technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we get, as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not hesitate to pay them
But France can only give the following justification: it "maintains" its commitment of 420 million euros, of which 91.5% is a loan (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% is a gift (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document so you can verify it yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses a loan to this extent.
Germany has claimed 46% of the proceeds, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) have fulfilled their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the absolute majority of the European Union gives <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to meet its promise, France gives only 10 cents and considers this effort comparable.
It's a beautiful piece of ice cream!
To sum up, in its financing of "fast start" France operates with two hedges: on the one hand with the development of the stock in time and on the other hand with a real financial burden.
Despite spending only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, he is able to convince that he is spending <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional" in connection with his promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such a decision) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would Member States continue to donate when it is enough to borrow?) and negotiate on the basis of developing countries
The early funding chapter is only a small issue, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could also be a grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw knowledge from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping the accounts for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of compliance with its obligations and fairness and justice towards the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussing long-term financing contributions (the other key chapters currently being discussed): we will not avoid the question of "additionality" or how to charge for loans.
France should change its position in order to become as progressive with these deposits as it is with others.
The hope is therefore that everyone will be joining the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizetova, who will come to Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement of France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans could lead to an increase in the level of international trust needed to be able to move forward in the discussions.
An alarm about pesticides that children will hate.
A 10-year-old child will one day be exposed to 81 different chemicals, according to a study published this Wednesday, from the Association of Future Generations (ex- Movement for the Rights and Preservation of Future Generations).
The association, which notes that its results "have no significant statistical value considering the low number of samples analyzed, but are characteristic of the processed problem", bought between July and September foods commonly consumed in a superlative dish in a bowl of four tablespoons of flour.
These typical foods, including official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day - as well as sugarcane, have been analyzed by research laboratories on chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals, and more.
The balance of the plate is staggering: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are listed among carcinogenic, possible or probable substances, and five substances belong to clear carcinogenic substances, as well as 37 substances that could act as a disruptive to the glands of the bladder.
"While in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, in our research we can see well that reality in the exposure of consumers to contaminants, possibly carcinogenic, and/or PE is infectious," he said.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk themselves contain about ten residues with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven as certain carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, presented in the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicide in France.
The same is true for green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, where the study found traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, steaks from ground meat, tuna in a can, and even mushrooms and chewing gum were sprayed with pesticides and other chemicals.
The presence of nitrogen and chloroform was detected in the water from the tap of the analysis.
The steak from salmon to dinner was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues discovered and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave did not avoid analysis.
The final risk for consumers of this “coke of contaminants” is likely to be underestimated,” the study says.
The Ecological Europe-Greens Association (EE-LV) has proposed to "face an emergency situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop "increased civilizational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) examined the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 were in cereals.
